</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 WHERE THE MORNING LIGHT'S STILL BLUE Personal Essays About Idaho edited by 
William Studebaker and Rick Ardinger (University of Idaho Press: $15.95; 200 
pp., paperback original). Idaho remains one of the most thinly populated 
regions in America: More than one-third of the state -- 20 million acres -- is 
national forest, and these brief essays celebrate the beauty of the rivers, 
forests and lakes.In "Flying Among the Osprey," Gino Sky articulates the love 
of nature the authors share: "I call the place where I live Rhymes Creek, for 
that is what this place does for me -- make my body rhyme in a way few places 
ever have." Lynn Langer Meeks offers a change of pace in "Ranching With the 
Wind in Sugar Loaf Valley," a comic piece about tending cattle during the harsh 
northern winter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
