<HEADLINE>
<P>
GEARS & GADGETS: LOOK WHAT THE STORK BROUGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JUDI DASH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Family travel always has had its challenges -- creating safe spaces for 
infants to play, keeping car seats clean in the presence of sticky fingers and 
sudden spills, making sure Junior can reach the tabletop in the absence of a 
booster seat and finding just the right carryalls for baby gear and other kids' 
stuff. The items below won't preclude cries of: "Are we there yet?" nor "I have 
to go to the bathroom," but they will come in handy for families on the go. 
Shipping and handling are not included in the prices. 
</P>
<P>
 Babies are a handful -- two handfuls, in fact -- so what to do about toting 
around diapers, bottles and other infant paraphernalia while remaining 
hands-free for the little one? Land's End, a distributor of upscale sportswear 
for adults and children, has developed a backpack diaper bag that solves the 
problem handily. The lightweight (1 1/4 -pound) navy nylon bag has two primary 
zippered compartments; a large one contains two insulated pockets for bottles, 
a removable zippered bag for dirty diapers or other soiled items, and a key 
ring; a smaller outside compartment unzips to reveal a see-through plastic 
toilet kit and a removable soft changing pad (25 inches by 12 inches). Two 
front pockets could hold adult items, such as a wallet, paperbacks, etc. The 
adjustable back-straps are padded for extra comfort. I found the bag efficient 
not only for carrying infant gear, but also as a beach bag for adult wet stuff, 
when baby's not around. 
</P>
<P>
 Backpack Diaper Bag (No. 2887-2121) is $29.50 from Land's End; (800) 356-4444. 
 
</P>
<P>
 Little kids are always struggling with too-tall table tops, and booster seats 
just aren't available everywhere. This neat item not only provides a ready 
boost of five inches, but also has a built-in place to store toys, coloring 
books, diapers, bottles or whatever. The brightly colored purple, green and 
yellow plastic seat (designed for ages 1 to 3) has a fold-out backrest and 
storage space under the seat lid. An adjustable safety strap secures the child 
and the seat to a chair. 
</P>
<P>
 When collapsed, the backrest becomes a handle for easy toting. The whole 
shebang weighs just two pounds. The portable booster seat is quite hard and 
junior may require a little pillow for maximum comfort. But it's great to have 
along in a car trunk in a pinch and can come in handy when other tots come to 
call. 
</P>
<P>
 Portable Booster Seat, with built-in toy tote (No. 101839) is $24.98 from 
Lillian Vernon; (800) 285-5555.  
</P>
<P>
 There comes an age -- a very young age -- when children are able to move 
around just enough to get into trouble. At home, a playpen can solve the 
problem, but what about on the road? 
</P>
<P>
 Evenflo, a manufacturer of children's furniture, recently introduced a 
collapsible travel crib/play yard that comes with its own mattress and fitted 
quilted sheet and a zippered carryall. The two side panels are a see-through 
mesh, the end panels are a solid material; one end has a removable toy bag. 
When set up, the playpen measures a comfy 38 inches by 25 inches by 22 inches 
high. 
</P>
<P>
 The crib fabric is a cheerful geometric-patterned nylon material, the frame is 
a solid plastic, both of which make for easy cleaning. Wheels at one end aid 
mobility. 
</P>
<P>
 This item's a winner; it's easy to set up and pack (the frame locks in place 
or collapses via rotating connector bars. The playpen stores easily in a car 
trunk or as checked baggage on an airplane, though it might be too big (31 
inches by 10 inches by 10 inches when collapsed) and a bit heavy (22 pounds) to 
get by as a carry-on bag. 
</P>
<P>
 Happy Camper Travel Crib and Play Yard is about $80. A slightly larger deluxe 
version is about $100. To find a store near you contact the manufacturer at 
(800) 233-5921.  
</P>
<P>
 The back seat of any car that plays host to young kids is usually a sticky 
collage of everything they've ever eaten there, not to mention crushed crayons 
and leaked ink. The Car Towel is a big soft felt-like pad bonded to vinyl to 
prevent wet stuff from penetrating through to the car upholstery. Used 
vertically the towel can be tied to a head rest and takes care of one kid's 
mess.  
</P>
<P>
 Used horizontally, it covers most of the seat, providing protection from a 
whole back-seat brood. 
</P>
<P>
 Car Towel (No . 728873) is $14.98 from Just Between Us, a mail-order company; 
(800) 546-2255 .Everybody needs a place to carry their stuff -- including kids. 
This multicolored zippered carryall and matching waist pack is big enough for 
plenty of toys, books and other neat essentials, but small enough to be 
kid-friendly. 
</P>
<P>
 The 17-inch by 13-inch by 6 1/2-inch carryall has a big zippered outside 
pocket, nylon web handles and an adjustable shoulder strap. The waist pack has 
large and small zippered pockets, an adjustable waist belt and buckle closure.  
</P>
<P>
 Kids Carry-all and Waist Pack kit, including child's name (up to 12 letters) 
is $19.98 from Lillian Vernon; (800) 285-5555. Specify primary color mix (No. 
780806) or pastel mix (No. 159206).  
</P>
